                xml:id="ttag80"
                ref="#person_036"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag80" type="person">
          Newton
        </name>
            </rs>, whose<lb/>
just Glory &amp; whose splendid discoveries<lb/>
covering the great Laws of the<lb/>
Universe absorbed the attention<lb/>
of the philosophers of the<lb/>
age &amp; made them almost<lb/>
regardless of inferior <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">inventions</hi>.<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">
               <rs xml:id="ttag81" ref="#person_246" type="person">
                  <name xml:id="tag81" type="person">
          Hooke
        </name>
               </rs>
            </del> in the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">geological speculations</hi>
            <lb/>
which were published after his death<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">posthumous</del>, assuming as a fact<lb/>
the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">existence</hi> of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">shells &amp; the</hi>
            <lb/>
remains of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">marine</hi> animals<lb/>
in rocks &amp; in hills of<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">considerable elevation</hi> draws<lb/>
the conclusion, that these strata<lb/>
must have been at some period<lb/>
covered by the sea: |_&amp; after reasoning<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="36"
                xml:id="pb-36"
                facs="#i36"/>
            <lb/>
upon the general <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">effects of earthquakes</hi>.<lb/>
&amp; of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">volcanic explosions</hi> He infers<lb/>
that there are no causes in<lb/>
Nature more probable than<lb/>
these for the elevation of land<lb/>
of <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">mountain</del> rocks &amp; of mountains<lb/>
from the Bosom of the waters.<lb/>
-. He brings forward many<lb/>
chemical instances to shew<lb/>
that <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">water</hi>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">is capable</add> of dissolving &amp; of<lb/>
depositing stoney matter &amp;<lb/>
that its agency is fully<lb/>
adequate to the formation<lb/>
of strata; |_&amp; He shews that<lb/>
both in modern &amp; in ancient<lb/>
times several <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">instances</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">cases</add> have<lb/>
occured <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">&amp;</del> of islands &amp; of<lb/>
tracts of Land, rising out of<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="37"
                xml:id="pb-37"
                facs="#i37"/>
            <lb/>
the sea in consequence of submarine<lb/>
Volcanoes. -<lb/>
- The ideas of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag82"
                ref="#person_246"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag82" type="person">
          Hooke
        </name>
            </rs> are conceived<lb/>
with boldness &amp; develloped with<lb/>
precision. In many <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">points</del> principal<lb/>
parts of Theory He had anticipated<lb/>
the modern <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag83"
                ref="#misc_100"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag83">
          plutonic
        </term>
            </rs> Philosophers;<lb/>
He seems however to have<lb/>
restrained his imagination. He<lb/>
has contented himself with<lb/>
demonstrating a certain part<lb/>
of the <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">existing</add> order of Nature<lb/>
without attempting a general<lb/>
system of the past changes<lb/>
of the globe &amp; of its<lb/>
future destiny. -<lb/>
- <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag84"
                ref="#person_387"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag84" type="person">
                  <hi rend="underline">Beccher</hi>
               </name>
            </rs> lived at the same<lb/>
period as <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag85"
                ref="#person_246"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag85" type="person">
          Hooke
        </name>
            </rs>; like <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag86"
                ref="#person_246"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag86" type="person">
          Hooke
        </name>
            </rs> He<lb/>
devoted his life to Science; but He<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="38"
                xml:id="pb-38"
                facs="#i38"/>
            <lb/>
selected one department &amp; directed<lb/>
to Geological Chemistry, the<lb/>
whole of the powers of his<lb/>
Mind.<lb/>
In his book called subterranean<lb/>
Philosophy published in Latin in 1669<lb/>
He has given some very beautiful<lb/>
details with regard to the mineral<lb/>
Kingdom &amp; has offered views of<lb/>
theory perfectly new - His ideas<lb/>
concerning combination &amp; decomposition<lb/>
are of the most accurate nature<lb/>
His notion of an inflammable principle<lb/>
formed the foundation of the<lb/>
Hypothesis of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag87"
                ref="#person_388"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag87" type="person">
          Stahl
        </name>
            </rs> - He gave<lb/>
to chemical Philosophy new<lb/>
dominions &amp; new instruments of<lb/>
investigation &amp; He attempted<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="39"
                xml:id="pb-39"
                facs="#i39"/>
            <lb/>
to form a general theory in<lb/>
which all the operations of<lb/>
Nature should be explained &amp;<lb/>
illustrated by experiments of<lb/>
human invention. -<lb/>
.- Beccher with the sound judgment<lb/>
of a true Philosopher assumes<lb/>
a certain primary order of<lb/>
things resulting from the creation<lb/>
of the Globe &amp; He applies<lb/>
his reasonings only to the solution<lb/>
of the phaenomena of the changes<lb/>
which have since <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">taken place</hi>.<lb/>
- <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Water <del rend="strikethrough">&amp;</del> in the mineral</hi> Kingdom<lb/>
&amp; elastic vapours He considers<lb/>
as the great agents which<lb/>
have altered the position of<lb/>
strata &amp; the direction of metallic<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="40"
                xml:id="pb-40"
                facs="#i40"/>
            <lb/>
veins &amp; from the decomposition<lb/>
of certain rocks by these natural<lb/>
agents He supposes that new<lb/>
ones have been formed of a<lb/>
much <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">softer nature</hi> &amp; fitted<lb/>
to become soils, &amp; to support<lb/>
vegetable life. -<lb/>
Beccher was born at Spire<lb/>
in 1645. He was for some<lb/>
time professor of medicine in <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag88"
                ref="#place_1128"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag88" type="place">
          Bavaria
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
but He was driven from <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag89"
                ref="#place_324"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag89" type="place">
          Germany
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
by envy &amp; persecution - <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag90"
                ref="#place_121"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag90" type="place">
          England
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
became his adopted country.<lb/>
He was patronized by the<lb/>
great <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">
               <rs xml:id="ttag91" ref="#person_103" type="person">
                  <name xml:id="tag91" type="person">
          Boyle
        </name>
               </rs>
            </hi>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">in consequence of</add>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">by</del> whose liberality<lb/>
He was enabled to study mineralogy<lb/>
in <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag92"
                ref="#place_021"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag92" type="place">
          cornwal
        </name>
            </rs>, to pursue his<lb/>
experimental researches &amp; <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">the</del> to<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="41"
                xml:id="pb-41"
                facs="#i41"/>
            <lb/>
produce <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">some of</add> those works in <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">Geology</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">Natural</add>
            <lb/>
Science, which will always confer<lb/>
honour on his name. -<lb/>
- <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag93"
                ref="#person_246"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag93" type="person">
          Hooke
        </name>
            </rs> &amp; Beccher had contented<lb/>
themselves with <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">partial views</hi>, |_&amp;<lb/>
