            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">written in 1693</del> He enters upon<lb/>
the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">great doctrines</hi> relating to<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the Globe</hi>; the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">primary</hi> creation,<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the deluge</hi> the changes that<lb/>
have been <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">since</add> produced <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">since</del> &amp;<lb/>
that will be produced in <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">future</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Ages</hi>. -<lb/>
- He assumes as the foundation of<lb/>
his <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">reasoning</hi> the account of the creation<lb/>
given in the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">sacred writings</hi>.<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="42"
                xml:id="pb-42"
                facs="#i42"/>
            <lb/>
And He attempts to shew that the<lb/>
Globe at its <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">creation</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">origin</add> must have<lb/>
existed in a state of <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">igneous</add> fusion <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <del rend="strikethrough">fire</del>
            </add>, in<lb/>
consequence of which it assumed<lb/>
its <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">spherical form</hi>; The heavier<lb/>
substances such as the metals<lb/>
He supposes to have <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">been</del> occupied<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">
               <unclear>first deposited afterward</unclear>
            </del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">the centre &amp; He conceives that the</add>
            <lb/>
rocks which chrystalized <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">&amp;</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">which though</del> at first in<lb/>
regular strata were afterwards<lb/>
broken <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">&amp; raised into mountains</add> by explosions taking<lb/>
place from <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">the centre</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">beneath</add> &amp; <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">the</del>
            <lb/>
chasms produced &amp; filled with<lb/>
metallic veins. -<lb/>
The water which at first<lb/>
existed in <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">highly rarified</add> vapor He supposed<lb/>
to have been by degrees<lb/>
condensed &amp; from its action<lb/>
in its heated state upon the<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="43"
                xml:id="pb-43"
                facs="#i43"/>
            <lb/>
Land He <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">supposes</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">conceives</add> that a part<lb/>
of the surface was decomposed<lb/>
broken down &amp; converted into<lb/>
a soil, on which by the Almighty<lb/>
fiat vegetables &amp; animals were<lb/>
made to exist &amp; the whole<lb/>
cloaked with beauty <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">&amp; rendered</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">subservient</hi> to the purposes<lb/>
of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the last</hi>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">created</add> &amp;<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">most perfect</hi> of<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">creature</del>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">beings. -</hi>
            <lb/>
-. <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag96"
                ref="#person_1005"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag96" type="person">
          Leibnitz
        </name>
            </rs> supposes that there<lb/>
may have been two causes<lb/>
for the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Deluge</hi>;- The elevation<lb/>
of Land in the former bed<lb/>
of the Ocean in consequence<lb/>
of explosions from the central<lb/>
ignited mass &amp; <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the passage</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">of the tail of a</hi> comet<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="44"
                xml:id="pb-44"
                facs="#i44"/>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">through the Atmosphere loaded</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">with <rs xml:id="ttag97" ref="#chemical_503" type="chemical">
                  <term xml:id="tag97">
          aqueous vapour
          
        </term>
               </rs>
            </hi>. By the<lb/>
first cause He explains the passage<lb/>
in Genesis "The fountains of<lb/>
the great deep were broken up"<lb/>
&amp; by the second , <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">the other sentence</add> "the windows<lb/>
of heaven were opened &amp; the rain<lb/>
was upon the Earth for forty<lb/>
days &amp; forty nights-"<lb/>
- <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag98"
                ref="#person_1005"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag98" type="person">
          Leibnitz
        </name>
            </rs> supposes that the principal<lb/>
changes which have taken place<lb/>
Since <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the deluge</hi> have depended<lb/>
either upon volcanic fires;<lb/>
or great inundations from<lb/>
the Ocean; &amp; He <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">supposes</del> conceives<lb/>
that fire &amp; water are <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">great</del>
            <lb/>
counterballancing powers, by<lb/>
which an order of things<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="45"
                xml:id="pb-45"
                facs="#i45"/>
            <lb/>
similar to the present will be<lb/>
maintained till the great<lb/>
&amp; general <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">conflagration</hi>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">predicted</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">in the Scriptures shall take</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">place.</del>
            <lb/>
